Wash and dry produce. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @onion{1}; mince a few slices until you have 1 TBSP (2 TBSP for 4 servings). Dice @tomato{1} into 1⁄2-inch pieces. Pick @dill{1/4%ounce} fronds from stems; roughly chop. Zest and quarter @lemon{1}.

Melt @butter{1%TBSP} (2 TBSP for 4 servings) in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add minced onion; cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}. Stir in @white rice{3/4%cup}, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, @water{1 1/4%cups} (2 1/4 cups for 4), and a pinch of @salt{}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to use.

In a #small bowl{}, combine tomato with as much dill as you like; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Set aside, stirring occasionally, until ready to serve. In a separate small bowl, combine @sour cream{1.5%tablespoon}, @mayonnaise{2%tablespoon}, half the @garlic powder{1%teaspoon} (you'll use the rest later), and a squeeze of lemon juice. Add @water{} 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency. Season with salt and pepper.

> This is your tangy lemon white sauce.

Heat a large drizzle of @olive oil{} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add sliced onion and cook, stirring occasionally, until just beginning to soften, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Open package of @diced skinless dark meat chicken{10%ounce} and drain off any excess liquid.

Add chicken, @onion powder{1%tablespoon}, half the @dried oregano{1%teaspoon} (all for 4 servings), remaining garlic powder, @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring occasionally and lowering heat if browning too quickly, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}; stir in as much lemon zest as you like. Taste and season with salt and pepper if desired.

Divide rice between #bowls{}. Top with chicken and tomato-dill relish in separate sections. Drizzle chicken with white sauce and serve with remaining lemon wedges on the side.

> Chicken is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.